README.md
     1ŌåÆ# go-multierror
    10ŌåÆ> **Note**: As of Go 1.20, the standard library provides [`errors.Join`](https://pkg.go.dev/errors#Join) which offers similar functionality for combining multiple errors. **For new projects, we recommend using `errors.Join` from the standard library.** This package provides additional features like custom formatting, the `Group` pattern for concurrent error collection, and utility functions (`Append`, `Flatten`, `Prefix`).
    11ŌåÆ
    12ŌåÆ## Migrating to `errors.Join`
    14ŌåÆ**Basic error aggregation:**
    15ŌåÆ```go
    16ŌåÆ// Before (go-multierror)
    17ŌåÆvar result error
    18ŌåÆresult = multierror.Append(result, err1)
    19ŌåÆresult = multierror.Append(result, err2)
    20ŌåÆreturn result
    21ŌåÆ
    22ŌåÆ// After (stdlib)
    23ŌåÆvar errs []error
    24ŌåÆif err1 != nil {
    25ŌåÆ    errs = append(errs, err1)
    26ŌåÆ}
      ŌåÆŌĆ”
   104ŌåÆ## Installation and Docs
   106ŌåÆInstall using `go get github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror`.
   107ŌåÆ
   108ŌåÆFull documentation is available at
   109ŌåÆhttps://pkg.go.dev/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror
   110ŌåÆ
   111ŌåÆ### Requires go version 1.13 or newer
   113ŌåÆ`go-multierror` requires go version 1.13 or newer. Go 1.13 introduced
   114ŌåÆ[error wrapping](https://golang.org/doc/go1.13#error_wrapping), which
   115ŌåÆthis library takes advantage of.
   116ŌåÆ
   117ŌåÆIf you need to use an earlier version of go, you can use the
   118ŌåÆ[v1.0.0](https://github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror/tree/v1.0.0)
   119ŌåÆtag, which doesn't rely on features in go 1.13.
   120ŌåÆ
   121ŌåÆIf you see compile errors that look like the below, it's likely that
   122ŌåÆyou're on an older version of go:
   123ŌåÆ
   124ŌåÆ```
      ŌåÆŌĆ”
   129ŌåÆ## Usage
   131ŌåÆgo-multierror is easy to use and purposely built to be unobtrusive in
   132ŌåÆexisting Go applications/libraries that may not be aware of it.
   133ŌåÆ
   134ŌåÆ**Building a list of errors**
   135ŌåÆ
   136ŌåÆThe `Append` function is used to create a list of errors. This function
   137ŌåÆbehaves a lot like the Go built-in `append` function: it doesn't matter
   138ŌåÆif the first argument is nil, a `multierror.Error`, or any other `error`,
   139ŌåÆthe function behaves as you would expect.
   140ŌåÆ
   141ŌåÆ```go
   142ŌåÆvar result error
   143ŌåÆ
